thentic feeling.  Both are produced and circulated through the media, especially through interactive technologies. The author argues that these two formations of voice are mutually constitutive and aligned with modern ideologies of democracy and neoliberal economic projects.  This ethnography is set during an extraordinary period in Nepal’s history that has seen a relatively peaceful 1990 revolution that re-established democracy, a Maoist civil war, and the massacre of the royal family.  These dramatic changes have been accompanied by the proliferation of intimate and political discourse in the expanding public sphere, making the figure of voice ever more critical to an understanding of emerging subjectivity, structural change and cultural mediation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunicationxPolitical aspectszNepalzKathmandu. 0aMass mediazNepalzKathmandu. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z978311062111240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095806740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520958067423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520958067/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles